WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:23.600 --> 00:26.273
(CHEERING)

00:29.440 --> 00:31.078
WHIT: Thank you. Thank you.

00:31.280 --> 00:33.714
But no, give yourselves a hand
because it was your hard work

00:33.880 --> 00:37.714
that gave Yardsham Inlet the best year
in the history of this agency.

00:37.880 --> 00:39.632
(CHEERING)

00:42.800 --> 00:45.268
Before we let all that success
go to our heads,

00:45.480 --> 00:48.517
we just thought we should get together
and reconnect with the fundamentals

00:48.680 --> 00:49.954
of what actually got us here.

00:50.120 --> 00:51.633
For that, I'm gonna turn it over

00:51.800 --> 00:54.633
to our resident
poet philosopher of product.

00:54.840 --> 00:56.319
The rebel command of brand.

00:56.480 --> 00:59.119
He's the guru
who terrifies Madison Avenue.

00:59.280 --> 01:00.793
(CHEERING)

01:00.960 --> 01:02.552
My partner, my better half,

01:02.720 --> 01:03.720
Howard Inlet.

01:03.800 --> 01:06.268
(CHEERING)

01:07.920 --> 01:08.920
(SOFTLY) Love you.

01:13.840 --> 01:15.831
- Yes!
- (CHEERING CONTINUES)

01:17.160 --> 01:20.994
Oh. What is your "why"?

01:22.720 --> 01:25.029
Why did you even get out
of the bed this morning?

01:25.200 --> 01:27.191
Why did you eat what you ate?

01:27.360 --> 01:29.510
Why did you wear what you wore?

01:29.680 --> 01:31.875
Why did you come here?

01:32.040 --> 01:34.520
Other than the fact that
I would fire you and hire someone else

01:34.560 --> 01:36.198
if you didn't show up for work, but...

01:36.360 --> 01:38.191
- (LAUGHING)
- Not that. The big "why."

01:39.680 --> 01:42.797
We're certainly not here
to just sell shit.

01:43.280 --> 01:45.157
We are here

01:45.320 --> 01:46.878
to connect.

01:48.360 --> 01:50.510
Life is about people.

01:51.360 --> 01:55.478
Advertising is about illuminating

01:55.640 --> 01:58.518
how our products and services

01:58.720 --> 02:00.950
will improve people's lives.

02:01.360 --> 02:02.839
Now,

02:03.000 --> 02:04.718
how do we do that?

02:05.600 --> 02:06.999
Love.

02:07.680 --> 02:09.032
Time.

02:09.720 --> 02:11.073
Death.

02:12.360 --> 02:17.036
Now these three abstractions
connect every single human being on Earth.

02:17.240 --> 02:18.434
Everything that we covet,

02:18.600 --> 02:20.272
everything that we fear not having,

02:20.440 --> 02:23.113
everything that we ultimately
end up buying

02:23.280 --> 02:25.157
is because at the end of the day

02:25.840 --> 02:27.558
we long for love,

02:28.240 --> 02:30.071
we wish we had more time,

02:30.760 --> 02:32.830
and we fear death.

02:33.720 --> 02:34.914
Love.

02:36.080 --> 02:37.229
Time.

02:38.600 --> 02:40.113
Death.

02:40.280 --> 02:42.077
Let's begin there.

04:07.440 --> 04:09.158
How long did this one take?

04:09.960 --> 04:11.154
Five days.

04:12.400 --> 04:13.674
That's pretty impressive.

04:14.120 --> 04:16.160
- Maybe he came back too soon.
- Are you kidding me?

04:16.360 --> 04:18.396
It's been six months
of this zombie routine.

04:18.560 --> 04:19.760
We can't indulge this anymore.

04:20.200 --> 04:22.236
Especially because

04:22.400 --> 04:24.277
we're getting fired by Danworth Financial.

04:24.440 --> 04:26.510
- (COUGHS)
- CLAIRE: What? You're kidding me.

04:26.680 --> 04:27.816
- No, Whit, come on!
- I'm sorry, what?

04:27.840 --> 04:29.280
But I just talked to them yesterday.

04:29.360 --> 04:31.256
WHIT: I know. Everybody's been doing
their best to cover,

04:31.280 --> 04:33.748
but that entire account
is built on Howard's relationship.

04:34.040 --> 04:36.056
Half our billings are built
on Howard's relationships.

04:36.080 --> 04:37.256
This is a disaster. This is a disaster.

04:37.280 --> 04:38.508
No. Not yet.

04:38.680 --> 04:41.194
We have an offer from Omnicom
for $17 a share...

04:41.360 --> 04:42.576
- Oh, come on!
- ...but they want an answer

04:42.600 --> 04:43.953
- by New Year's.
- Shh.

04:44.840 --> 04:45.875
(BELL RINGS)

04:47.520 --> 04:49.875
(WHISPERING) Let's be honest,
we're not worth $14 a share

04:50.040 --> 04:51.320
if my partner takes a sabbatical

04:51.400 --> 04:53.197
as the local domino champion
of Crazy Town.

04:53.360 --> 04:54.480
That's a little harsh, Whit.

04:54.640 --> 04:56.517
WHIT: I'm sorry, but it's true.

04:56.680 --> 04:59.035
Simon, I am empowering you.
Go make the deal with Omnicom.

04:59.600 --> 05:01.989
I wish I could,
but Howard controls the voting shares.

05:02.200 --> 05:03.456
I'll deal with the Howard part, okay?

05:03.480 --> 05:04.674
Just push the papers, Simon.

05:05.560 --> 05:06.595
(FESTIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

05:06.760 --> 05:09.877
CLAIRE: I still don't understand
why Howard got 60% of the voting shares

05:10.080 --> 05:11.149
and you only got 40.

05:11.400 --> 05:13.595
Because I needed cash to settle my divorce

05:13.760 --> 05:16.718
and Howard did me a huge favor
and let me sell him some.

05:16.920 --> 05:21.072
So, if you never had an affair
with some junior creative,

05:21.240 --> 05:22.536
we wouldn't be in this situation?

05:22.560 --> 05:24.391
Inaccurate and unfair

05:24.560 --> 05:26.790
to put it squarely on my shoulders.

05:26.960 --> 05:29.394
- Well, I'm just pointing out the facts.
- (BELLS TINKLING)

05:30.040 --> 05:33.237
Oh, my God.
Don't you just love that smell?

05:33.440 --> 05:34.793
Wait. Stop.

05:34.960 --> 05:36.359
Close your eyes.

05:36.560 --> 05:37.993
Breathe it in.

05:38.920 --> 05:41.150
Doesn't that remind you of your childhood?

05:42.640 --> 05:43.914
Claire, come here.

05:46.920 --> 05:48.512
Come on, I got to tell you something.

05:49.720 --> 05:50.720
What?

05:51.560 --> 05:54.279
I have been doing something
about our situation

05:54.440 --> 05:56.112
that you need to know about.

05:56.280 --> 05:57.280
What did you do?

05:57.440 --> 05:58.759
I hired someone.

05:58.960 --> 05:59.995
You hired someone?

06:00.280 --> 06:03.238
Yes. Look, when Eloise caught me cheating,

06:03.400 --> 06:06.949
she used a private investigator
named Sally Price.

06:07.120 --> 06:09.176
She's this woman
who looks like a Mormon grandmother,

06:09.200 --> 06:11.953
and it makes her very good
at the whole stealth thing.

06:12.240 --> 06:14.356
You hired the woman
who caused your divorce?

06:14.880 --> 06:16.552
No. I caused my divorce.

06:16.720 --> 06:19.154
Sally Price just documented it.

06:19.760 --> 06:22.274
Wow. That was actually enlightened.

06:22.920 --> 06:24.990
I have hidden depth. We've discussed this.

06:25.440 --> 06:26.634
So,

06:26.800 --> 06:28.438
why did you hire the Mormon grandmother?

06:28.600 --> 06:31.433
Because we need to document
what's going on with Howard.

06:31.640 --> 06:35.394
We need to show that
he's not mentally fit to vote his shares.

06:35.640 --> 06:38.154
No. We're not really
in that place where we're...

06:38.320 --> 06:41.437
We're actually gonna be the people
who would do that to a friend?

06:41.600 --> 06:42.749
It's not that he won't sell,

06:42.960 --> 06:47.317
it's that he won't even
have a conversation about selling.

06:47.480 --> 06:50.119
I try to talk to him, I try to reach him,

06:50.280 --> 06:52.760
and it's like I'm not even
in the same physical space with him.

06:52.880 --> 06:53.880
He's not there.

06:54.040 --> 06:55.996
His kid died.

06:56.320 --> 06:58.515
That was two years ago, Claire.

06:58.800 --> 06:59.994
What are we gonna...

07:00.160 --> 07:02.071
This is our lives at stake.

07:02.240 --> 07:04.080
We're not kids anymore.
You look me in the face

07:04.120 --> 07:06.496
and tell me that you're willing to have
everything you've worked for

07:06.520 --> 07:08.636
for the last 10 years just evaporate.

07:13.200 --> 07:14.519
Is this PI good?

07:14.680 --> 07:16.477
She caught me cheating.

07:16.640 --> 07:18.120
Oscar could have caught you cheating.

07:18.200 --> 07:19.679
Who the hell's Oscar?

07:19.840 --> 07:20.840
My son.

07:21.040 --> 07:22.996
Oh. (STAMMERING) That Oscar?

07:23.160 --> 07:25.160
This private investigator
isn't gonna find anything

07:25.200 --> 07:27.031
that'll pass for moral turpitude.

07:27.880 --> 07:29.871
(WHISPERING) Not on Howard,

07:30.040 --> 07:32.759
but if she can raise concern
regarding legal capacity,

07:32.920 --> 07:34.069
then we'll be in business.

07:34.240 --> 07:36.674
I do really think that
we are out of other options.

07:36.840 --> 07:39.673
You know, he terrorized
the grief counselor for six months.

07:39.840 --> 07:43.549
He totally blew off the Ayahuasca shaman
we flew in all the way from Peru.

07:43.720 --> 07:46.393
And our...
Our intervention was a disaster.

07:46.560 --> 07:47.834
I just...

07:48.720 --> 07:51.757
Look, uh, this doesn't feel right.

07:52.320 --> 07:53.799
I know.

07:53.960 --> 07:56.633
But when something starts
with a six-year-old dying,

07:56.800 --> 07:58.472
nothing is gonna feel right.

08:14.440 --> 08:15.634
(CHUCKLES)

08:18.480 --> 08:20.596
(CHILD LAUGHING)

08:30.920 --> 08:32.068
(GASPS)

08:40.080 --> 08:41.274
(SIGHING)

10:10.280 --> 10:12.510
(HORN HONKING)

10:20.240 --> 10:21.240
SALLY: He writes letters.

10:21.360 --> 10:23.237
CLAIRE: Letters? What kind of letters?

10:23.400 --> 10:25.960
SALLY: This might be the strangest thing
I have ever come across.

10:26.040 --> 10:27.951
- You got the letters?
- Oh, yeah.

10:28.120 --> 10:29.917
SIMON: Can we ask you how?

10:30.200 --> 10:32.509
Cost me $800

10:32.680 --> 10:33.749
to get this cut.

10:33.920 --> 10:34.920
And just so you know,

10:35.080 --> 10:38.277
it's a federal offense
to steal mail directly from a mailbox.

10:38.520 --> 10:40.670
- You could...
- Yeah.

10:40.840 --> 10:43.115
- So, three letters.
- Who are they to?

10:43.280 --> 10:44.600
- Oh, not who.
- What do you mean?

10:44.760 --> 10:46.320
Howard doesn't write letters to people.

10:46.400 --> 10:47.799
He writes to things.

10:48.000 --> 10:49.831
- WHIT: What kind of things?
- Time.

10:51.280 --> 10:53.032
Love.

10:53.560 --> 10:54.595
Death.

10:54.920 --> 10:56.592
The three abstractions.

10:56.800 --> 10:57.915
CLAIRE: "Time,

10:58.080 --> 11:00.355
"they say you heal all wounds,

11:00.520 --> 11:02.431
"but they don't talk about how you destroy

11:02.640 --> 11:03.840
"all that's good in the world.

11:04.360 --> 11:06.555
"How you turn beauty into ash.

11:07.120 --> 11:10.192
"Well, you're nothing more
than petrified wood to me.

11:10.360 --> 11:13.591
"You're a dead tissue
that won't decompose.

11:13.760 --> 11:14.760
"You're nothing."

11:14.920 --> 11:17.070
That doesn't prove anything.
We can't use that, right?

11:17.280 --> 11:19.271
No. I mean,
kids write letters to Santa Claus,

11:19.440 --> 11:20.640
it doesn't mean they're crazy.

11:20.720 --> 11:23.075
No. This is therapeutic.

11:24.240 --> 11:25.514
It's so sad.

11:25.760 --> 11:27.591
Yeah. Anything else?

11:28.160 --> 11:31.232
Usually after work,
he goes to a small dog park in Brooklyn,

11:31.400 --> 11:33.436
even though he doesn't own a dog.

11:33.600 --> 11:35.113
Just sits there for hours.

11:35.400 --> 11:36.760
Does he write letters to the dogs?

11:37.680 --> 11:38.680
Are you serious?

11:38.960 --> 11:40.576
Well, that would be
like the home run, right?

11:40.600 --> 11:42.079
I mean, that's what we need.

11:43.120 --> 11:45.111
- Does he?
- Not that I saw.

11:45.760 --> 11:47.352
- Okay. What else?
- That's it, really.

11:47.560 --> 11:50.233
Goes home to his apartment.
Rarely leaves before morning.

11:50.400 --> 11:52.675
No Wi-Fi, cable, phone. Nothing.

11:53.920 --> 11:57.959
"You're a dead tissue
that won't decompose."

11:58.960 --> 12:00.951
(HORNS HONKING)

12:07.360 --> 12:09.430
(SIREN WAILING)

12:19.640 --> 12:20.834
Howard?

12:21.680 --> 12:23.318
Hey, it's Claire.

12:24.680 --> 12:27.990
I swung by that place down the street
and got you some dinner.

12:31.320 --> 12:33.834
It's that shrimp thing you like.

12:36.720 --> 12:39.837
Okay, I'm gonna leave it right here,
in case you haven't eaten.

12:41.120 --> 12:42.680
Hey, don't keep leaving the food there.

12:42.760 --> 12:43.760
He doesn't eat it.

12:44.000 --> 12:45.672
Oh, I'm... I'm sorry.

12:45.840 --> 12:47.478
And he's late on his rent again.

12:47.640 --> 12:50.256
He doesn't answer his door,
and I don't have a working number for him.

12:50.280 --> 12:52.555
Yeah, he doesn't have a phone anymore.

12:53.520 --> 12:57.513
(SIGHS) Um, how much does he owe?
I'll write you a check.

12:57.680 --> 12:59.557
SUPER: If that's what you want to do.

12:59.960 --> 13:02.679
And, uh, if you're not doing anything
with that shrimp...

13:03.400 --> 13:06.039
Broccoli rabe last week was delicious.

13:15.280 --> 13:17.555
(HORN HONKING)

13:24.040 --> 13:25.837
(HORN HONKING)

13:37.960 --> 13:40.554
(FESTIVE MUSIC PLAYING)

14:05.680 --> 14:07.557
Here he is.

14:08.360 --> 14:09.588
Hey, where's your stuff?

14:10.800 --> 14:13.075
I wanted to text you,
but Mom said I had to call.

14:13.240 --> 14:14.434
Text me about what?

14:14.600 --> 14:17.478
But then Barry said
I had to tell you in person.

14:17.760 --> 14:19.751
Are we taking life advice from Barry now?

14:20.040 --> 14:21.576
What are...
What are you trying to tell me?

14:21.600 --> 14:22.999
I'm not coming to stay with you.

14:23.280 --> 14:24.776
I'm going with Barry and Mom
to the Bahamas.

14:24.800 --> 14:27.314
No, no. Wait, wait, wait.

14:28.800 --> 14:29.869
Hi.

14:31.320 --> 14:32.514
How you doing?

14:32.840 --> 14:35.400
Can I get, like, five minutes,
maybe a couple feet

14:35.600 --> 14:37.636
just to have this conversation
with my daughter?

14:41.720 --> 14:42.789
Thanks.

14:43.960 --> 14:45.188
Honey, I got...

14:45.400 --> 14:46.536
I got all kinds of stuff planned.

14:46.560 --> 14:47.736
I got a Christmas tree for us.

14:47.760 --> 14:48.795
Then sucks for you.

14:48.960 --> 14:50.096
I got us tickets to Hamilton.

14:50.120 --> 14:51.519
Then sucks for Hamilton.

14:51.680 --> 14:53.033
That's a tough ticket, Allison.

14:53.240 --> 14:54.389
I've already seen it.

14:55.480 --> 14:57.550
(STAMMERS) You did?
You saw that with Mom and Barry?

14:57.800 --> 14:59.153
And Odell Beckham Jr.

14:59.520 --> 15:00.839
And Odell Beckham?

15:01.160 --> 15:02.559
Yeah.

15:02.720 --> 15:04.119
He's one of Barry's friends.

15:07.160 --> 15:08.309
Why?

15:10.920 --> 15:12.296
Why don't you want to spend
the holiday with me?

15:12.320 --> 15:13.639
I miss you.

15:14.040 --> 15:15.473
Because I hate you.

15:15.680 --> 15:17.398
Because you're a philanthropist.

15:17.600 --> 15:19.750
Because you broke Mom's heart.

15:20.680 --> 15:23.148
- (STAMMERS) Philanderer.
- ALLISON: What?

15:24.840 --> 15:27.016
The word you're looking for
is philanderer, not philanthropist.

15:27.040 --> 15:28.600
They have a slightly different meaning.

15:28.680 --> 15:30.398
Well, you would know.

15:30.600 --> 15:31.874
Mmm-hmm.

15:34.880 --> 15:37.189
Look, I agreed to tell you in person,
and now I have.

15:44.720 --> 15:45.755
Hey,

15:45.960 --> 15:47.632
have a good Christmas.

15:47.840 --> 15:49.990
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

16:03.360 --> 16:04.634
Hold it.

16:06.360 --> 16:07.554
Hey.

16:13.680 --> 16:14.999
(ELEVATOR BUTTON CLICKS)

16:16.720 --> 16:18.631
So, rapid fire round while I got you?

16:18.800 --> 16:20.392
Cavs are in town.

16:20.560 --> 16:22.232
Christmas showdown at the Garden.

16:23.160 --> 16:24.718
I never give your seat away.

16:24.920 --> 16:26.990
I just go solo, but we could go.

16:27.160 --> 16:29.640
Don't even have to talk.
Don't even have to look at each other.

16:29.720 --> 16:32.016
We can do just what we're doing right now
and just watch the game.

16:32.040 --> 16:33.439
Be like old times.

16:35.320 --> 16:36.548
Right, number two.

16:36.760 --> 16:38.016
We're gonna lose the Danworth account

16:38.040 --> 16:39.800
because that's always been
your relationship.

16:39.840 --> 16:42.149
And they're not feeling the love,
as you might imagine.

16:42.320 --> 16:43.320
So that's gonna happen.

16:45.560 --> 16:47.596
Whatever though,

16:47.760 --> 16:50.115
because we've got an offer
from Omnicom, and it's real.

16:50.320 --> 16:51.878
17 bucks a share.

16:52.760 --> 16:54.318
Please consider it, because...

16:54.480 --> 16:55.959
Yeah, yeah.

16:56.160 --> 16:59.436
Because they leave total creative control
and they let everybody keep their jobs,

16:59.600 --> 17:02.160
which I know you care about,
because you love these people.

17:04.839 --> 17:05.839
Good talk.

17:12.319 --> 17:14.595
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

17:34.760 --> 17:36.079
The Beijing boys are here.

17:36.280 --> 17:38.157
Oh, God. No one wants Chinese coffee.

17:38.320 --> 17:39.355
Well, we're selling it.

17:39.520 --> 17:42.193
The Manchurian macchiato. Mmm.

17:42.800 --> 17:43.994
What are we casting?

17:44.160 --> 17:45.880
- Cruise line.
- Now, see, that's good copy.

17:46.040 --> 17:48.600
"Shed your skin, find your life."

17:48.760 --> 17:50.193
Sorry, it's

17:50.360 --> 17:52.920
"Life is found when you shed your skin."

17:53.080 --> 17:55.594
- Does it really matter?
- Yes, because I wrote it.

17:55.840 --> 17:58.593
Oh, well, my way's better.

17:58.840 --> 18:00.159
- Really? How?
- AMY: Yeah.

18:00.320 --> 18:01.833
Well... Wait, what is your way?

18:02.000 --> 18:04.036
BOTH: "Life is found
when you shed your skin."

18:04.200 --> 18:07.158
Which, you know, kind of hits you here.

18:07.920 --> 18:11.435
"Shed your skin, find your life."

18:11.600 --> 18:12.874
Hits you here.

18:14.360 --> 18:15.429
That does hit me here.

18:15.640 --> 18:17.198
Right?

18:17.360 --> 18:18.360
You can have it for free.

18:18.520 --> 18:20.317
Just, wait. Wait.

18:20.480 --> 18:21.674
Wait.

18:25.040 --> 18:26.189
- Hey, Frankel.
- Yeah?

18:26.360 --> 18:28.078
"Shed your skin, find your life."

18:28.240 --> 18:30.310
"Shed your skin, find your life."
Everybody, okay?

18:30.480 --> 18:31.480
Got it.

18:32.520 --> 18:33.953
She made it better.

18:38.920 --> 18:40.035
WHIT: Hey!

18:45.800 --> 18:46.869
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

18:47.080 --> 18:48.308
No, no, no.

18:50.520 --> 18:51.555
Hey, hey!

19:00.440 --> 19:02.396
(HORN HONKING)

19:17.600 --> 19:19.477
- (TIRES SCREECHING)
- (HORN HONKING)

19:28.160 --> 19:30.151
BRIGITTE: "And you talk to me
in such tones

19:30.320 --> 19:32.959
"as if it wasn't the breath in my lungs
that gave you life."

19:33.120 --> 19:34.633
- You're late.
- AMY: Sorry.

19:34.800 --> 19:36.756
"As if it wasn't a spark in my mind

19:36.920 --> 19:38.592
"that gave that life meaning."

19:38.760 --> 19:40.910
"Oh, you move your tongue,
you mouth syllables,

19:41.080 --> 19:42.752
"you echo sentiment.

19:42.920 --> 19:44.148
"But you do not breathe."

19:44.320 --> 19:45.389
"You speak of spark?

19:45.760 --> 19:46.988
"That is richness.

19:47.200 --> 19:49.350
"For you deny the spark between us all.

19:49.520 --> 19:53.399
"A spark that is more a sun
than the cold fire you claim.

19:55.080 --> 19:57.799
"And you have called me
a temporary madness.

19:57.960 --> 19:59.188
"A vicious soul.

19:59.360 --> 20:00.793
"Well,

20:00.960 --> 20:04.919
"then ask if you will see me
just one more time."

20:05.760 --> 20:07.113
Hello?

20:07.680 --> 20:08.795
Hi.

20:09.960 --> 20:12.076
So sorry. I literally just wandered in,

20:12.240 --> 20:14.959
and I caught the tail end of that, and...

20:15.400 --> 20:17.960
Can I just say that was beautiful?

20:18.120 --> 20:19.155
What is... What is it?

20:19.360 --> 20:21.216
It's just something
we're trying to put together.

20:21.240 --> 20:23.117
I just... I love theater. I see everything.

20:23.320 --> 20:24.776
So when's opening night? I'll be there.

20:24.800 --> 20:27.234
There is no opening night
until we get this money together.

20:27.400 --> 20:29.436
- You rich?
- Divorced.

20:29.800 --> 20:31.597
You followed me from the casting session.

20:31.760 --> 20:33.671
- WHIT: Absolutely, I did. Yes.
- Yeah.

20:33.840 --> 20:36.149
WHIT: I almost lost you,
but the red hat helped.

20:36.320 --> 20:39.630
Hey, um, I'm gonna say something
a little impulsive here,

20:39.840 --> 20:40.840
maybe a little crazy,

20:41.000 --> 20:43.560
but, you know, uh, I have something
about to happen for me.

20:43.760 --> 20:48.072
I'm in the middle of a deal
that if it all comes together,

20:48.280 --> 20:49.679
I'd be in a position to help.

20:49.840 --> 20:51.671
Well, now wouldn't that be lovely?

20:52.520 --> 20:54.317
WHIT: It would. Be great.

20:54.520 --> 20:56.158
And you, you know, you fixed it.

20:56.320 --> 20:59.596
So, we should get you back into casting
if you want the gig. I mean...

21:00.680 --> 21:03.240
Sorry, I don't even...
I don't know your name.

21:04.840 --> 21:06.910
- Amy.
- WHIT: Amy.

21:07.080 --> 21:09.435
Okay. Well,

21:09.600 --> 21:12.751
I'll be back, Amy. I'll be back.

21:12.920 --> 21:15.229
Mmm. And I'll be...

21:15.800 --> 21:17.756
Hmm. Sorry.

21:18.000 --> 21:19.274
(CHUCKLING) I was on the stage!

21:19.440 --> 21:20.919
I'll be back.

21:22.040 --> 21:23.234
You're good.

21:27.640 --> 21:29.119
Well done, you.

21:41.840 --> 21:44.070
(DOGS BARKING)

21:44.720 --> 21:46.358
(INDISTINCT POLICE RADIO
CHATTER ON TV)

21:46.560 --> 21:48.073
Apartment next door is vacant,

21:48.280 --> 21:50.510
but the guy down the hall
says he didn't hear anything.

21:50.680 --> 21:52.113
Ditto the manager.

21:52.440 --> 21:54.556
Wait, they have a CSI: Cleveland now?

21:54.720 --> 21:56.616
- MAN: Neighborhood like this...
- It's a new show.

21:56.640 --> 21:58.039
Minding their own business.

21:58.200 --> 22:01.829
WOMAN: What's a respectable
neurosurgeon doing in a crack house?

22:02.000 --> 22:03.115
MAN: I don't know.

22:03.280 --> 22:04.918
The werewolves,

22:05.080 --> 22:06.911
they're meeting out front

22:07.080 --> 22:08.991
all hours of the night.

22:09.160 --> 22:10.559
(DOGS BARKING)

22:12.080 --> 22:13.593
I heard them. Yeah.

22:15.160 --> 22:16.752
I think they're...

22:16.920 --> 22:19.559
I think they're voting
on a new head of the syndicate.

22:19.800 --> 22:20.869
But

22:21.800 --> 22:24.439
I got a raccoon friend.
He's on the task force.

22:24.600 --> 22:26.636
He put a bug out there for me
by the trash cans.

22:26.800 --> 22:28.597
We're gonna tape everything they say

22:28.880 --> 22:31.110
and we'll bust them on a RICO statute.

22:32.200 --> 22:34.111
I don't know anything about that.

22:37.200 --> 22:39.191
Hey, I'm your son.

22:40.960 --> 22:42.837
(CHUCKLING) I know that!

22:44.400 --> 22:46.118
Good.

22:50.960 --> 22:52.279
I'll be right back.

23:18.800 --> 23:20.472
Okay, I have kind of a wild idea.

23:20.640 --> 23:21.776
And I know you're gonna laugh at me,

23:21.800 --> 23:23.760
but remember that we're desperate
and hear me out.

23:23.880 --> 23:27.759
So, my mom hasn't been totally
in her right mind since her stroke, right?

23:27.920 --> 23:30.639
And I'm always trying to remind her
what's actually going on

23:30.840 --> 23:33.229
and correct the, sort of,
daffy things that she says.

23:33.400 --> 23:35.296
And it upsets her,
and it really stresses me out.

23:35.320 --> 23:37.056
And it was pretty much just awful
for a while.

23:37.080 --> 23:39.640
And then, someone said something
very, very wise to me.

23:39.800 --> 23:44.749
They said, "Maybe you should stop
trying to force your reality on her

23:44.920 --> 23:47.992
"and just...
Just go into her reality."

23:48.160 --> 23:49.991
I thought you couldn't
afford therapy anymore.

23:50.160 --> 23:51.991
- I can't. It was my Uber driver.
- Oh.

23:52.600 --> 23:54.511
And he was totally right.
Totally right!

23:54.680 --> 23:57.672
As soon as I started doing this,
everything got easier, you know?

23:57.840 --> 23:59.831
Our life is like
this improvisational game.

24:00.040 --> 24:03.430
She just... She says wackadoodle stuff,
and I respond to it.

24:03.600 --> 24:07.036
And, uh, she's totally happy
and I kind of have fun.

24:07.640 --> 24:09.576
- And that made me think of something else.
- Mmm.

24:09.600 --> 24:11.352
Okay.

24:13.040 --> 24:14.189
When I was at FBW,

24:14.360 --> 24:16.376
I had this account
for a psychostimulant drug, right?

24:16.400 --> 24:18.360
And they went with some
bullshit generic campaign,

24:18.560 --> 24:20.216
- but I kept the Hispanic market.
- (SPEAKING SPANISH)

24:20.240 --> 24:21.355
Here, watch this. Okay.

24:21.560 --> 24:23.755
So, the teacher is really stressing.
He's saying, uh,

24:23.920 --> 24:25.956
"Well, you talk all the time!
You never listen!"

24:26.120 --> 24:27.917
And then here comes the monster.

24:28.080 --> 24:29.376
"It doesn't have to be this way."

24:29.400 --> 24:31.391
Teacher, "Who are you?"

24:31.560 --> 24:32.993
Monster, "I'm your anger, man."

24:33.200 --> 24:34.200
And the teacher says...

24:34.800 --> 24:36.640
"I can't stand you, man.
You dominate my life."

24:36.800 --> 24:39.598
And anger says,
"There's a solution, my friend.

24:40.440 --> 24:43.557
"Docotrin, say goodbye to your anger."

24:45.080 --> 24:46.593
Do you see where I'm going with this?

24:46.800 --> 24:50.190
- (SIGHS) Not really.
- Okay, okay. Look, look.

24:50.960 --> 24:54.555
We can't get Howard to deal with this
reality that we need him to deal with.

24:54.760 --> 24:57.433
And he's writing letters to abstractions
which makes no sense.

24:57.640 --> 24:59.551
But... But he's doing it.

24:59.720 --> 25:01.950
So, what if we just go into his reality

25:02.120 --> 25:04.759
and we get those abstractions
to answer him?

25:05.840 --> 25:07.159
I'm sorry, I... I don't follow.

25:07.320 --> 25:11.950
What if Love, Time and Death
show up in person

25:12.120 --> 25:14.429
and answer the letters
that Howard's been writing to them?

25:14.600 --> 25:18.434
How are Time, Love and Death
gonna show up?

25:18.760 --> 25:20.591
Actors.

25:20.760 --> 25:24.150
We hire actors to be Love, Death and Time.

25:24.320 --> 25:27.471
They find Howard and they confront him.

25:30.080 --> 25:32.640
So, you want us to gaslight your boss?

25:33.040 --> 25:36.191
- Huh? I'm sorry?
- Gas Light.

25:36.360 --> 25:38.120
You know? It was a play,
then it was a movie.

25:38.280 --> 25:39.998
Gas Light? Oh, my God.

25:40.160 --> 25:43.948
Does nobody ever watch anything
longer than eight seconds anymore?

25:44.120 --> 25:47.635
What she's saying is
you want us to make him think he's crazy?

25:47.800 --> 25:51.395
No, no, no. It's not about
making Howard think he's crazy.

25:51.560 --> 25:55.473
Howard's not in a good mental state,
and we know that.

25:55.640 --> 26:00.873
It's about underlining that fact
so that other people can see it, too.

26:01.080 --> 26:05.358
Okay. So you want us to perform
in this intervention,

26:05.520 --> 26:08.592
and for that
you're gonna finance our play?

26:08.800 --> 26:09.869
- That's it.
- Exactly.

26:10.040 --> 26:12.031
Yeah, we'll finance whatever...

26:12.200 --> 26:13.896
I mean, this looks
like a storage facility, but...

26:13.920 --> 26:16.354
Okay. Well, actors. What do we think?

26:16.520 --> 26:18.988
- No. No, no, no.
- Oh, no.

26:19.160 --> 26:20.160
Listen, listen!

26:20.320 --> 26:21.673
We take $15,000 each.

26:21.840 --> 26:24.593
- Okay? $15,000.
- AMY: Are you completely out of your mind?

26:24.760 --> 26:26.512
Okay, we'll do it.

26:26.680 --> 26:28.033
$20,000, each.

26:28.200 --> 26:31.510
Uh-uh! I just... You guys just said 15.
I heard you say 15.

26:31.960 --> 26:33.996
- Mmm... I like 20.
- I like 20 as well.

26:34.160 --> 26:36.240
Well, 20's just...
I don't know, it's a little steep.

26:36.360 --> 26:38.656
I'm like... I was thinking two.
These guys probably live in Brooklyn.

26:38.680 --> 26:40.336
- They pay 600 bucks a month.
- Stop talking. Just stop.

26:40.360 --> 26:41.536
You did a good job pulling them down.

26:41.560 --> 26:43.240
This is horrible.
This is completely wrong.

26:43.280 --> 26:47.114
No, Amy. This is the work. This is acting.

26:47.280 --> 26:49.520
Did you not hear them say
that this man's lost his child?

26:49.680 --> 26:53.150
Yes. And that's why he's reaching out
to the cosmos for answers.

26:53.320 --> 26:56.232
Well, we get to be that cosmos.

26:56.400 --> 27:00.518
Okay, so you want us to manipulate
this guy's pain so that, what?

27:00.720 --> 27:02.551
What, you cash out?
You make a lot of money?

27:03.040 --> 27:04.200
- SIMON: No!
- No, no, no, no!

27:04.280 --> 27:05.696
That doesn't sound good
when you put it that way.

27:05.720 --> 27:08.029
- It's a lot more complicated than that.
- Is it?

27:08.200 --> 27:09.235
CLAIRE: We love this man.

27:09.520 --> 27:11.636
And he's not just a boss, he's a friend.

27:12.560 --> 27:15.472
Howard is a brilliant,
creative, charismatic guy

27:15.880 --> 27:16.880
who used to be fearless.

27:17.040 --> 27:19.110
He used to love life,
and right now, he hates it.

27:19.600 --> 27:22.068
And you really think
that this is gonna help him?

27:22.280 --> 27:23.713
CLAIRE: He lost his child.

27:24.440 --> 27:26.908
And now he doesn't care
if he loses everything else.

27:27.120 --> 27:29.429
We just can't let that happen.

27:29.600 --> 27:31.272
We have to bring him back.

27:33.000 --> 27:34.228
$20,000's worth it.

27:34.400 --> 27:35.656
- (STAMMERING) I'll pay for it.
- Claire!

27:35.680 --> 27:37.910
I'll pay for it. I'll pay for it myself.
I don't care.

27:38.280 --> 27:41.238
So, what are the rules?

27:41.400 --> 27:44.233
Well, first, we'd have to sign
a confidentiality agreement.

27:44.400 --> 27:46.256
And make sure
that you don't talk about it, 'cause...

27:46.280 --> 27:47.576
No, I don't mean the legal rules.

27:47.600 --> 27:49.397
I mean, the rules
of the theatrical device.

27:49.600 --> 27:53.513
I mean, do other people see us,
or only Howard?

27:54.200 --> 27:56.760
- Yeah, do other people see them, Whit?
- Whit?

27:56.920 --> 27:59.673
I guess... I guess only Howard.

27:59.840 --> 28:01.831
That's the effect
we're looking for, right?

28:02.000 --> 28:03.479
- Guess?
- You guess? I mean...

28:03.640 --> 28:05.280
I'm sorry, have you thought this through?

28:05.440 --> 28:06.793
- Sure. Sure.
- No.

28:06.960 --> 28:08.176
- I mean, to a degree.
- No, we haven't.

28:08.200 --> 28:10.555
No, we haven't, Whit. Shut up! Like...
We haven't.

28:10.720 --> 28:13.632
For instance, what if they go into a bar
and they want to order a drink?

28:13.800 --> 28:14.869
How can they do that if...

28:15.040 --> 28:16.936
Do you see Howard walking
into a lot of bars these days?

28:16.960 --> 28:18.188
Whatever. Doesn't matter.

28:18.360 --> 28:20.016
- I mean, what if Howard goes clubbing?
- They're actors.

28:20.040 --> 28:22.838
- They need to know hypothetically.
- Okay. Okay. Enough. Enough.

28:23.000 --> 28:26.436
We have the power to be seen
by whomever we want, whenever we want.

28:26.640 --> 28:28.312
- How's that?
- I like that, I like that.

28:28.480 --> 28:30.136
- I told you they were good.
- I like that, yeah.

28:30.160 --> 28:31.440
We should just leave it to them.

28:31.480 --> 28:32.549
Let's move on.

28:32.720 --> 28:33.720
What's next?

28:33.880 --> 28:36.792
Well, Howard wrote three letters
to Love, Death and Time.

28:36.960 --> 28:39.997
So, I guess the only question is
who plays who?

28:40.160 --> 28:42.071
Casting. Very important.

28:42.640 --> 28:43.834
Love.

28:45.200 --> 28:46.599
Death.

28:47.320 --> 28:48.320
Time.

28:49.320 --> 28:51.629
Great. When do we get paid?

29:17.840 --> 29:21.150
BRIGITTE: "Dear Death,
you travel with so much mythology,

29:21.360 --> 29:24.352
"cause so much pain, inspire such fear.

29:24.680 --> 29:26.591
"But you're a paper tiger to me.

29:26.760 --> 29:29.877
"You're just pathetic
and powerless middle management.

29:30.080 --> 29:32.640
"You don't even have the authority
to make a simple trade."

29:32.800 --> 29:35.837
As you can see,
it's not exactly a fan letter.

29:36.040 --> 29:38.200
- Yeah, well, Death doesn't have any fans.
- (COUGHING)

29:38.240 --> 29:41.676
I don't understand why,
because it's a liberation.

29:42.680 --> 29:44.716
Hey, you okay?

29:44.920 --> 29:46.239
Mmm-mmm.

29:55.960 --> 29:58.190
CLAIRE: He goes to work, and the dog park.

29:58.600 --> 29:59.874
And that's it.

30:00.040 --> 30:01.553
Okay. So, here's how I'm gonna do it.

30:01.720 --> 30:03.199
I'm gonna come to him angry.

30:03.400 --> 30:05.550
Like, pissed off. Like, we got a problem.

30:05.720 --> 30:08.029
No, no, no. Don't do that.

30:08.240 --> 30:11.232
He's calling me wood and dead tissue.
He's calling me out.

30:11.400 --> 30:12.400
How's he calling you out?

30:12.560 --> 30:13.754
Time.

30:13.920 --> 30:16.832
He's calling out Time, and I'm Time.

30:18.360 --> 30:20.555
Look, I don't want
you antagonizing Howard.

30:20.720 --> 30:22.073
Do you get that?

30:37.320 --> 30:40.232
AMY: But the letter only consists
of one word, "Goodbye."

30:40.920 --> 30:41.920
Look.

30:42.080 --> 30:44.071
"Dear Love, goodbye."

30:44.400 --> 30:46.914
What am I even supposed to say to him?

30:47.160 --> 30:49.276
Um, it's...

30:50.600 --> 30:52.016
It's a letter to Love
saying goodbye, right?

30:52.040 --> 30:53.712
- Yeah.
- So, what if you approach him,

30:53.880 --> 30:55.393
and you refuse to accept that?

30:55.560 --> 30:57.835
You say he can't
get rid of you that easily.

30:58.040 --> 30:59.234
Tell him that

31:00.480 --> 31:04.234
we don't get to choose who we love
and who loves us back.

31:04.600 --> 31:07.956
Tell him that you're within him,

31:08.480 --> 31:12.029
you're within everything,
whether he likes it or not.

31:12.440 --> 31:14.271
And if he accepts that,

31:15.320 --> 31:18.153
then maybe... I don't know.

31:18.320 --> 31:21.915
Maybe he gets to find his life again.

31:56.560 --> 31:57.754
(DOG YIPPING)

32:14.240 --> 32:15.673
They grieve.

32:17.440 --> 32:19.078
Dogs.

32:19.240 --> 32:22.471
They grieve,
and they fully understand death.

32:25.560 --> 32:27.755
You called me a paper tiger.

32:28.920 --> 32:30.273
In the letter you wrote me.

32:30.440 --> 32:31.998
You said I was pathetic.

32:33.720 --> 32:34.869
Mmm.

32:35.080 --> 32:36.308
You don't remember?

32:36.480 --> 32:38.710
You went on about middle management,

32:38.880 --> 32:41.997
making a deal, paper tiger.

32:43.480 --> 32:46.153
Oh, Howard, it wasn't that long ago.

32:47.520 --> 32:49.476
Where did you get that?

32:49.880 --> 32:53.316
- Who are you?
- Who did you write the letter to?

32:54.200 --> 32:55.679
(CHUCKLES)

32:56.680 --> 32:58.159
I wrote the letter to Death.

33:00.160 --> 33:03.038
Nice to meet you. Charmed, I'm sure.

33:05.120 --> 33:06.314
No.

33:07.240 --> 33:08.240
I know, I know.

33:08.400 --> 33:10.550
People write letters
to the universe all the time.

33:10.720 --> 33:12.551
Most don't get a personal response.

33:12.760 --> 33:16.070
But you are, because I just wanted
to tell you that you're wrong.

33:16.240 --> 33:18.037
I'm not some powerless middle management

33:18.200 --> 33:19.520
- just following orders.
- Miss...

33:19.720 --> 33:22.075
You see, I didn't want to make
the trade. It was my call.

33:22.240 --> 33:24.231
I don't want this. I don't want this.

33:24.400 --> 33:26.040
Now, I don't tell you how to do your job.

33:26.120 --> 33:29.112
So, I'd appreciate it
if you didn't tell me how to do mine.

33:30.120 --> 33:32.634
Who's that man talking to?
He looks kind of weird.

33:32.800 --> 33:35.951
Don't worry about that.
Sometimes people are silly.

33:36.120 --> 33:38.714
You see, they don't see me
till it's their time.

33:38.880 --> 33:40.996
Oh, it's okay, Howard.
It's not your time yet.

33:41.200 --> 33:42.713
I just wanted to return this

33:44.160 --> 33:46.594
and clear things up between us.

33:49.480 --> 33:52.040
- I really am Death, Howard!
- (DOG YIPPING)

33:57.440 --> 33:58.440
He believed me.

33:58.640 --> 34:00.232
I'm telling you he believed me.

34:00.400 --> 34:02.834
- That's amazing.
- I mean, that was spectacular.

34:03.000 --> 34:04.616
Because there was no safety net, you see.

34:04.640 --> 34:06.040
That... That... That was Grotowski.

34:06.120 --> 34:08.634
- That was pure Stella Adler!
- Ah!

34:08.840 --> 34:10.800
- Thank you. Thank you for the opportunity.
- Yes.

34:10.840 --> 34:12.016
- You are a kind man.
- Oh, not a problem.

34:12.040 --> 34:13.856
- He believed me, I'm telling you.
- I wouldn't go that far.

34:13.880 --> 34:16.096
But he needed it.
I could tell. I could tell in his eyes.

34:16.120 --> 34:18.416
Who was that woman and that little boy?
That was incredible.

34:18.440 --> 34:20.576
Oh, that was our private investigator
and her grandson.

34:20.600 --> 34:22.750
Oh, really?
And did she say anything about me?

34:22.920 --> 34:24.797
She said you were good.
She said really good.

34:25.000 --> 34:26.295
"Good"? What do you mean? Good like...

34:26.320 --> 34:28.436
You mean good like cabbage is good,
or what?

34:28.600 --> 34:30.636
No, no. She... (STAMMERS) Great.

34:30.800 --> 34:34.315
She said, she said,
"She made the impossible possible."

34:34.480 --> 34:36.835
- (CHUCKLES) I should be paying you.
- (BOTH LAUGH)

34:39.159 --> 34:42.469
They told me that Trevor had
packed his little suitcase,

34:42.679 --> 34:44.830
that he said he was going home.

34:45.679 --> 34:47.159
I was furious.

34:48.199 --> 34:51.829
But he was sleeping,
so I couldn't talk to him.

34:52.840 --> 34:57.630
I mean, what nurse promises
this dying five-year-old little boy

34:57.800 --> 34:59.438
he could go home?

35:00.320 --> 35:02.834
He barely had any white blood cells left.

35:03.680 --> 35:05.318
He was so fragile.

35:06.720 --> 35:08.631
And who could be so cruel?

35:09.600 --> 35:10.919
Who could do that?

35:12.240 --> 35:13.912
So, of course I'm frantic.

35:14.080 --> 35:18.471
I am shouting at the staff,
trying to get to the bottom of it.

35:19.800 --> 35:22.394
Well, Trevor finally wakes up

35:22.560 --> 35:24.755
and I go to him.

35:24.920 --> 35:31.029
You know, his little blue suitcase
was still at the edge of the bed, right.

35:31.920 --> 35:34.559
So, I look at him and ask,

35:35.640 --> 35:37.676
"Who said that to you, sweetie?

35:38.720 --> 35:41.393
"Who said that you could
come back to our house?"

35:42.000 --> 35:43.672
You know what he says?

35:45.080 --> 35:46.877
"Nobody, Mommy.

35:48.520 --> 35:50.954
"I'm not going back to our house.

35:51.720 --> 35:53.233
"I'm going home."

35:58.920 --> 36:02.435
He died four hours later.

36:03.880 --> 36:05.074
(DOOR OPENS)

36:07.240 --> 36:09.390
(WOMAN SOBS)

36:18.520 --> 36:19.839
Hello.

36:21.040 --> 36:22.314
Hi.

36:23.040 --> 36:25.429
Are you looking
for Smallest Wings Support Group?

36:26.400 --> 36:27.913
Um...

36:28.960 --> 36:31.838
- Yes.
- And you are?

36:34.120 --> 36:37.078
- Um, Howard.
- Howard.

36:38.280 --> 36:40.510
Come on in. Have a seat.

36:53.040 --> 36:54.951
Did you lose a child, Howard?

36:55.640 --> 36:56.959
Yeah.

36:57.120 --> 36:58.633
- MADELINE: Boy or girl?
- Uh...

36:59.040 --> 37:00.109
A girl.

37:02.080 --> 37:03.479
And what was her name?

37:09.480 --> 37:11.675
No, it's okay. Howard.

37:12.640 --> 37:14.631
You don't have to answer.

37:15.560 --> 37:18.279
You don't even have to talk, okay?

37:20.000 --> 37:21.592
You stick around?

37:23.080 --> 37:24.308
Please?

37:30.080 --> 37:31.274
Okay.

37:31.440 --> 37:32.998
Thank you so much for sharing.

37:33.320 --> 37:34.548
We really appreciate it.

37:34.720 --> 37:35.720
Thank you.

37:36.520 --> 37:38.988
Does anybody have anything else
they'd like to say?

37:55.520 --> 37:58.512
- So, why'd you decide to come in tonight?
- Hmm?

37:59.160 --> 38:02.357
Yeah, I've... I've seen you outside.

38:02.520 --> 38:05.353
I was gonna come out one night
and invite you in,

38:05.520 --> 38:07.476
but I guess I didn't want
to blow up your spot.

38:07.800 --> 38:10.030
- Blow up my spot?
- (CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

38:10.200 --> 38:12.191
- Yeah.
- You didn't want to mess up my jam?

38:12.360 --> 38:14.237
(CHUCKLES)

38:14.720 --> 38:16.153
Exactly.

38:17.720 --> 38:18.869
What's your name?

38:21.520 --> 38:22.589
I'm Madeline.

38:23.120 --> 38:24.758
Nice to meet you.

38:26.280 --> 38:28.032
My daughter's name was Olivia.

38:28.240 --> 38:31.755
She died of a rare form of brain cancer
known as Glioblastoma Multiforme,

38:31.920 --> 38:33.239
or GBM for short.

38:33.400 --> 38:35.152
She was six years old.

38:37.120 --> 38:38.917
What was your daughter's name, Howard?

38:46.080 --> 38:47.399
Okay.

38:47.560 --> 38:50.552
Fine. Don't answer.
I'm not gonna torture you.

38:50.760 --> 38:52.113
Thank you.

38:52.280 --> 38:54.794
- Was it the holidays?
- Mmm?

38:54.960 --> 38:56.871
Why you decided to come in tonight.

38:57.040 --> 38:59.838
We get a lot of first-timers
during the holidays.

39:00.000 --> 39:02.389
- No, that's not it.
- Then why tonight?

39:03.480 --> 39:05.914
Uh, I guess...

39:07.480 --> 39:08.480
I'm, uh...

39:09.840 --> 39:12.912
I'm trying to fix my mind.

39:14.720 --> 39:16.870
You lost a child, Howard.

39:17.640 --> 39:19.471
It'll never be fixed.

39:25.120 --> 39:26.951
I hope you come back.

40:13.480 --> 40:14.480
Hey.

40:14.680 --> 40:16.910
Signed contracts
and confidentiality agreements.

40:17.080 --> 40:19.355
- Oh, great. Thank you.
- So, did he say something?

40:19.560 --> 40:20.834
Who, Howard?

40:21.000 --> 40:23.761
- No. Unfortunately, he didn't.
- Oh, he believed it, I'm telling you.

40:23.840 --> 40:25.616
- Oh, that's good.
- Maybe you should send me in again.

40:25.640 --> 40:27.676
Not Raffi. Raffi's too impetuous.

40:27.840 --> 40:29.671
And Amy, she's just so emotional.

40:29.840 --> 40:31.512
After me, what is there?

40:31.680 --> 40:33.113
Well, he did write three letters.

40:33.320 --> 40:35.276
But Death is so much more vital than Time.

40:35.440 --> 40:37.954
- Right.
- Death gives Time all of its value.

40:38.160 --> 40:40.879
Maybe... Maybe I should
play all the parts.

40:41.360 --> 40:44.670
You know the highest margin demographic
is new parents now?

40:44.840 --> 40:46.320
Target actually invented an algorithm

40:46.480 --> 40:48.576
to predict when their female customers
were gonna get pregnant.

40:48.600 --> 40:50.875
You said before that you weren't okay.

40:51.200 --> 40:52.519
Are you sick?

40:55.960 --> 40:57.188
I'm sick.

40:59.040 --> 41:00.712
You could say, uh, I'm very sick.

41:05.800 --> 41:07.199
You're dying?

41:09.880 --> 41:11.199
Everyone's dying.

41:14.240 --> 41:16.196
Yeah, but you're doing it now.

41:18.720 --> 41:21.075
Simon. Simon.

41:21.800 --> 41:24.872
Come on, tell me. Tell me.
What is it? What's wrong?

41:26.040 --> 41:27.758
What's wrong?

41:27.960 --> 41:30.235
What's wrong is that
I came out of remission

41:30.400 --> 41:31.913
two weeks before my son was born.

41:32.520 --> 41:33.794
What's wrong

41:34.920 --> 41:37.520
is that I'm running a marathon every day
pretending to be healthy.

41:37.720 --> 41:38.948
That's what's wrong.

41:40.880 --> 41:42.313
Have you told anyone?

41:45.360 --> 41:46.554
You haven't?

41:46.960 --> 41:49.793
No, just some pushy actress
that I don't really know.

41:55.480 --> 41:57.436
What is it?

41:58.000 --> 41:59.149
It's multiple myeloma.

42:00.400 --> 42:03.710
I fought it when I was 16,
and then again when I was 25.

42:05.000 --> 42:07.195
It just never went away.

42:07.360 --> 42:09.954
Instead it regrouped and got stronger.

42:12.360 --> 42:14.191
So, the war's over?

42:18.280 --> 42:20.396
Yeah, war's over.

42:22.440 --> 42:24.874
Are your affairs in order?

42:25.680 --> 42:26.908
My affairs are not in order.

42:27.680 --> 42:29.477
That's why I hired you.

42:29.960 --> 42:31.640
It's bad enough that
I'm leaving my family.

42:31.760 --> 42:33.751
I'm not gonna leave them penniless.

42:36.480 --> 42:37.799
He believed me.

42:38.640 --> 42:39.675
Howard.

42:40.840 --> 42:43.149
He believed me.

42:51.640 --> 42:54.598
HOWARD: Hey. Excuse me.
No, don't touch that.

42:54.800 --> 42:56.313
I don't understand dominoes.

42:56.480 --> 42:59.836
There's no board to play them on,
or basket to throw them into.

43:00.000 --> 43:01.353
Right. Um...

43:01.520 --> 43:03.120
I think you might be in the wrong place.

43:03.160 --> 43:04.991
No, I'm in the right place, Howard.

43:08.080 --> 43:10.469
Mmm. Yeah.

43:12.120 --> 43:15.556
"Time, they say you heal all wounds,

43:15.720 --> 43:18.917
"but they don't talk about how you destroy
all that's good in the world.

43:19.600 --> 43:22.592
"How you turn beauty into ash."

43:22.760 --> 43:24.478
Now that's some bullshit, Howard.

43:24.960 --> 43:28.236
If Love is creation
and Death is destruction,

43:29.080 --> 43:31.310
I'm just a terrain in between.

43:32.280 --> 43:35.192
You don't understand Time.
No one understands Time.

43:35.360 --> 43:38.158
I mean, Einstein came close
when he said I was an illusion.

43:38.320 --> 43:39.514
CLAIRE: Howard? Hey. Uh...

43:39.720 --> 43:40.869
Listen, I'm sure it's a "no"

43:41.040 --> 43:44.032
but Oneida Apparel asked that
you be in the media buy meeting.

43:45.200 --> 43:46.918
I'm sorry to just barge in.

43:48.360 --> 43:49.793
Ask her.

43:49.960 --> 43:52.713
Go ahead. Ask her if she can see me.

44:03.040 --> 44:04.320
I'm not gonna be in the meeting.

44:05.720 --> 44:07.392
Mmm-hmm.

44:07.560 --> 44:08.754
Well, they insisted I ask.

44:09.080 --> 44:10.616
I mean, they're probably
gonna fire us, so...

44:10.640 --> 44:11.675
Okay.

44:11.840 --> 44:12.989
- Awesome.
- Yes.

44:13.160 --> 44:14.195
Okay.

44:15.240 --> 44:16.559
See you later.

44:19.480 --> 44:21.232
RAFFI: You can have this back, Howard.

44:21.400 --> 44:23.231
Why did you write me anyway?

44:23.400 --> 44:24.913
You wrote me because you need me.

44:25.080 --> 44:26.399
No. Um...

44:26.600 --> 44:28.397
I don't need anything from you, okay?

44:28.600 --> 44:30.636
You all like to bitch and complain.

44:30.800 --> 44:32.631
"There isn't enough time."

44:32.800 --> 44:34.677
"Life is short."

44:34.840 --> 44:36.910
"Oh, here, the gray hairs are coming in."

44:37.080 --> 44:38.911
You know, a day is long as hell.

44:39.080 --> 44:41.958
I'm abundant. I'm a gift.

44:42.120 --> 44:44.315
Even while you're
standing here talking shit,

44:44.480 --> 44:46.914
I'm gifting you, and you're wasting it.

44:47.120 --> 44:48.120
On what?

44:48.280 --> 44:49.952
I mean, what is this? Huh?

44:51.800 --> 44:53.279
Hey, hey!

44:53.600 --> 44:54.635
You know,

44:54.800 --> 44:57.268
I should be the one
that's writing angry letters.

45:05.800 --> 45:07.916
That was the worst thing I've ever done.

45:08.120 --> 45:10.076
That was the best thing I've ever done.

45:10.400 --> 45:13.073
What was that thing you said
about Einstein in there?

45:13.240 --> 45:16.630
Einstein called time
a stubbornly persistent illusion.

45:17.920 --> 45:19.239
What's that even mean?

45:19.560 --> 45:21.676
Time doesn't go from January to December,

45:21.840 --> 45:23.478
or from noon to midnight.

45:23.640 --> 45:25.915
You know, we all just make it that way
in our heads.

45:26.280 --> 45:27.793
That's absurd.

45:27.960 --> 45:30.758
Try telling that to a person
who's an hour late to a wedding

45:30.920 --> 45:34.708
or was just sentenced to 20 years in jail.
(SCOFFS)

45:35.040 --> 45:36.360
Or someone fighting a baby clock.

45:38.200 --> 45:41.988
We really don't need
to have this conversation, ever.

45:43.520 --> 45:45.317
Anyway, just...

45:45.480 --> 45:48.119
Yeah, wanted to say great job today.

45:49.000 --> 45:51.150
Just a stubborn illusion, Claire.

45:51.320 --> 45:52.992
You have all the time in the world.

45:53.640 --> 45:54.959
You're nine!

45:56.520 --> 45:57.839
"You're nine."

46:14.480 --> 46:15.480
Hi.

46:18.600 --> 46:20.431
I'm sorry.

46:22.560 --> 46:24.755
I'm so sorry.

46:25.280 --> 46:26.633
Um...

46:28.760 --> 46:30.955
You gotta be friggin' kidding me.

46:31.120 --> 46:32.473
I'm eating.

46:34.160 --> 46:35.878
You said goodbye, and that...

46:36.360 --> 46:40.399
(SIGHS) We don't get to choose
who we love or who loves us back.

46:41.240 --> 46:43.536
And that means you're powerless to me
as long as you're alive

46:43.560 --> 46:45.312
because I'm the fabric of life.

46:45.480 --> 46:48.074
I'm within you. I'm within everything.

46:48.800 --> 46:49.835
Howard,

46:50.640 --> 46:52.232
if you can accept that, then maybe...

46:52.400 --> 46:56.109
I don't know,
but maybe you get to live again.

47:14.560 --> 47:16.516
I completely screwed it up.

47:17.160 --> 47:18.479
I was weepy and apologetic.

47:18.640 --> 47:20.480
Well, I think love can be
weepy and apologetic.

47:20.600 --> 47:21.880
I think I was better at the end.

47:22.040 --> 47:24.634
Hey, hey. I'm sure you were great.

47:25.080 --> 47:26.399
You're sweet.

47:26.600 --> 47:27.600
Can I kiss you?

47:27.840 --> 47:29.398
You don't have to sexualize it.

47:29.640 --> 47:32.029
I can kiss you without sexualizing it.

47:32.240 --> 47:34.470
Seriously, I've had sex
without sexualizing it.

47:34.640 --> 47:36.437
You should take "sweet," Whit.

47:36.920 --> 47:38.194
It's a promotion.

47:39.440 --> 47:41.351
"Irresistible" would be a promotion.

47:42.320 --> 47:43.320
He believes it.

47:43.480 --> 47:44.833
How could you tell?

47:46.200 --> 47:47.758
I could tell by his eyes.

47:47.920 --> 47:50.912
That's great, but no one else has seen it

47:51.080 --> 47:53.040
and that's ultimately
what we need to have happen.

47:53.120 --> 47:56.271
We think if you would engage with him

47:56.440 --> 47:59.273
- one more time, um, in public.
- Great. Mmm-hmm.

47:59.600 --> 48:01.113
WHIT: But this time try to...

48:01.280 --> 48:03.794
SIMON: But you need to provoke
a strong visible reaction.

48:03.960 --> 48:04.960
Why?

48:05.160 --> 48:08.118
Because our private investigator's
gonna capture it on video.

48:08.320 --> 48:09.456
And we're gonna use it as evidence.

48:09.480 --> 48:10.720
It'll be like being in a movie.

48:11.800 --> 48:13.200
Except you'll be digitally removed.

48:13.920 --> 48:14.920
No.

48:15.320 --> 48:16.320
Sorry?

48:16.480 --> 48:17.629
This is too intense.

48:17.840 --> 48:19.456
Um, I'm sorry. I can't be a part of this.

48:19.480 --> 48:22.313
Amy, there is no "too intense" in acting.

48:22.480 --> 48:25.552
Do you wanna be loved
or do you wanna make an impact?

48:25.720 --> 48:28.154
I mean, this isn't Nol Coward.

48:28.320 --> 48:29.753
This is... This is Chekhov.

48:29.920 --> 48:31.148
This is horrible!

48:31.640 --> 48:34.438
The... You know,

48:34.640 --> 48:37.791
you did start the agency
with him, didn't you, Whit?

48:37.960 --> 48:39.393
And, Claire, he was your mentor.

48:39.600 --> 48:42.273
And, Simon, he gave you part
ownership in a business

48:42.480 --> 48:44.072
when he absolutely didn't have to.

48:44.240 --> 48:45.976
- I may have told her a few things...
- Mmm-hmm.

48:46.000 --> 48:47.200
- ...when we were...
- Mmm-hmm.

48:47.360 --> 48:48.680
AMY: I'm sorry, this is horrible.

48:48.840 --> 48:50.976
I... I can't...
No, I can't be a part of this. Thank you.

48:51.000 --> 48:52.040
- Sorry. Thanks.
- Amy, no.

48:52.160 --> 48:53.195
Amy.

48:53.360 --> 48:54.360
Amy. No.

48:54.520 --> 48:55.880
Oh, she's so passionate, you know.

48:56.000 --> 48:57.000
Amy!

48:57.360 --> 48:59.112
I'm so sorry. She will be back.

48:59.280 --> 49:01.271
But if she isn't, um,

49:01.440 --> 49:04.512
I'll step in. I do know all about love.

49:06.000 --> 49:07.194
Amy!

49:13.840 --> 49:14.955
What'd I miss?

49:17.480 --> 49:19.550
People crying because their kids died.

49:19.720 --> 49:21.756
Hmm. Uh...

49:22.920 --> 49:27.038
Uh, there's a thing called
bereavement hallucinations.

49:27.360 --> 49:28.360
Yes.

49:28.560 --> 49:29.754
Right. Um. Okay.

49:29.960 --> 49:32.349
So, uh...

49:32.560 --> 49:34.118
I looked them up.

49:34.320 --> 49:36.788
And here's the thing. I don't sleep.

49:37.000 --> 49:38.000
Okay.

49:38.200 --> 49:40.077
(STAMMERING) Like, not a lot.

49:40.240 --> 49:41.719
I mean, I sleep.

49:42.400 --> 49:43.549
Mmm.

49:44.400 --> 49:48.712
But I get six or seven hours a week.

49:49.240 --> 49:51.196
Now that I think about it,
that's probably why...

49:51.360 --> 49:52.360
Why what?

49:53.000 --> 49:54.194
Um...

49:55.240 --> 49:56.514
(SIGHS)

49:58.760 --> 50:02.070
I'm having conversations.

50:03.240 --> 50:04.559
Mmm-hmm.

50:07.440 --> 50:10.159
I mean, conversations.

50:10.920 --> 50:12.239
Okay.

50:15.040 --> 50:17.838
It's okay. Never mind. Um...

50:18.200 --> 50:20.270
- Howard?
- Yeah.

50:21.120 --> 50:22.951
You wanna have a conversation with me?

50:24.560 --> 50:26.039
Uh, yes.

50:29.600 --> 50:32.592
So, I assume you're a part of the 79%?

50:32.920 --> 50:33.955
Mmm?

50:34.200 --> 50:38.034
Of couples who get divorced
after losing a child.

50:38.400 --> 50:39.992
Yeah.

50:40.240 --> 50:41.240
Mmm.

50:41.440 --> 50:42.793
Yeah, me too.

50:45.560 --> 50:46.959
Do you still love her?

50:49.640 --> 50:52.108
I don't even know what love is anymore.

50:53.440 --> 50:55.112
Do you still love him?

50:55.320 --> 50:57.038
We never fell out of love.

50:57.880 --> 51:00.155
At least, I don't think so. It's just...

51:01.280 --> 51:02.429
We can...

51:03.160 --> 51:04.354
(SIGHS)

51:08.280 --> 51:12.637
The day our divorce was final,
he sent me this.

51:18.160 --> 51:20.913
"If only we could be strangers again."

51:22.160 --> 51:23.752
Now we are.

51:25.320 --> 51:27.709
The most romantic gesture he ever made.

51:29.000 --> 51:31.230
So, to answer your question,

51:31.760 --> 51:32.909
yes,

51:33.080 --> 51:34.513
I still love him.

51:43.200 --> 51:44.758
What did you mean

51:44.920 --> 51:46.616
when you said
you were having conversations?

51:46.640 --> 51:47.640
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

51:47.800 --> 51:49.756
- Conversations with who?
- Um...

51:50.600 --> 51:51.953
It's not "who."

51:52.120 --> 51:53.348
It's really... It's...

51:53.520 --> 51:55.511
You're gonna think I'm crazy.

51:55.680 --> 51:56.680
Try me.

51:56.880 --> 51:58.996
Um, can I show you?

51:59.720 --> 52:03.349
MADELINE: "Dead tissue
that won't decompose."

52:04.480 --> 52:06.471
He was sitting right here.

52:06.680 --> 52:11.037
Just a mean, little, arrogant thug.

52:11.760 --> 52:14.672
And he was the first one
that appeared, right?

52:15.040 --> 52:17.031
Uh, no. Death came first.

52:17.200 --> 52:19.953
She met me in the dog park.

52:20.760 --> 52:22.478
Oh, so Death is a "her"?

52:22.840 --> 52:27.118
Uh, yeah. It turns out
Death is an elderly white woman.

52:29.040 --> 52:30.393
What was the trade?

52:31.240 --> 52:33.754
You said Death wouldn't make the trade.

52:34.240 --> 52:35.240
What does that mean?

52:35.400 --> 52:37.197
When we realized our...

52:37.880 --> 52:41.839
My daughter was dying, I prayed, uh...

52:43.080 --> 52:47.039
Not to God or the universe, but to Death.

52:47.200 --> 52:48.918
I offered a trade.

52:49.080 --> 52:50.752
Take me,

52:50.920 --> 52:52.592
leave my daughter.

52:55.160 --> 52:59.073
But she didn't wanna make the trade, so...

53:17.560 --> 53:19.278
BRIGITTE: So, who won that round?

53:20.560 --> 53:22.357
You or the porcelain?

53:22.520 --> 53:25.432
(CHUCKLES) Porcelain.
Porcelain's undefeated.

53:27.240 --> 53:29.754
I'm sorry about that,
I thought everyone left.

53:29.920 --> 53:32.115
Yes, they did. But I'm here to close up.

53:32.280 --> 53:33.315
SIMON: Good.

53:33.520 --> 53:34.600
You need help getting home?

53:34.960 --> 53:36.473
No. I'm fine.

53:36.920 --> 53:38.592
I'm... I'm good.

53:40.160 --> 53:41.388
I Googled you.

53:41.600 --> 53:42.600
- You did?
- Yeah.

53:42.760 --> 53:43.760
(WHISPERS) Oh, God.

53:43.960 --> 53:45.791
You came from nothing.

53:46.600 --> 53:48.636
You put yourself through Duke,

53:49.120 --> 53:51.156
you married a wonderful woman,

53:51.320 --> 53:52.594
you're a loving father.

53:52.760 --> 53:54.990
So, you lived well. You lived right.

53:58.000 --> 54:00.468
But, my friend, you're not dying right.

54:01.000 --> 54:02.797
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

54:03.000 --> 54:04.638
Are you gonna tell me how to die?

54:04.840 --> 54:06.353
Have you told your family yet?

54:08.480 --> 54:10.675
- Mmm-mmm.
- You're not helping them.

54:11.000 --> 54:13.753
You're just denying them
what is rightfully theirs.

54:13.920 --> 54:15.239
Yeah? And what's that?

54:15.400 --> 54:17.914
Pain? Atrophy? Disease?

54:18.080 --> 54:19.513
Yes. Yes.

54:19.680 --> 54:21.159
All of it.

54:21.520 --> 54:23.988
And the chance to say goodbye.

54:27.600 --> 54:28.669
Stick to acting.

54:36.320 --> 54:37.753
MADELINE: Okay.

54:37.960 --> 54:40.633
I have something
that I haven't told anyone.

54:41.400 --> 54:44.676
It doesn't involve letters
or angels or anything like that,

54:45.880 --> 54:47.154
but it means something to me.

54:50.840 --> 54:56.233
They were preparing Olivia to say goodbye.

54:57.160 --> 55:01.233
And my husband was trying to
calm my mother in the parking lot

55:01.440 --> 55:03.237
because she lost it.

55:05.040 --> 55:06.837
So I was alone

55:07.760 --> 55:10.672
and I was sitting there
in the waiting room

55:10.840 --> 55:12.796
at Maimonides Hospital.

55:13.960 --> 55:16.872
And there was this woman
